---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-australia', text: 'Leaving Australian Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'reciprocal-agreements', text: 'Reciprocal Agreements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-australia', text: 'Returning to Australia', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best Asia Insurance', href: '/best/asia-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best UK Expat Insurance', href: '/best/uk-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'New Zealand Expat Insurance', href: '/best/new-zealand-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'asiaNetwork', header: 'Asia Network' },
  { key: 'globalNetwork', header: 'Global Network' },
  { key: 'australiaCoverage', header: 'Australia Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', asiaNetwork: 'Strong', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', australiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'AUD 280/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', asiaNetwork: 'Excellent', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', australiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'AUD 320/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', asiaNetwork: 'Good', globalNetwork: 'Strong', australiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'AUD 260/mo' },
  { provider: 'NIB Global', asiaNetwork: 'Good', globalNetwork: 'Good', australiaCoverage: 'Included', price: 'AUD 240/mo' },
  { provider: 'Medibank Global', asiaNetwork: 'Limited', globalNetwork: 'Limited', australiaCoverage: 'Included', price: 'AUD 220/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Australian Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Australian expats. Find coverage that works when you leave Medicare behind and avoid LHC loading when you return."
  headline="Best Insurance for Australian Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Medicare doesn't follow you overseas. Here's how to stay covered abroad—and avoid lifetime health cover loading when you return."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/australian-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Australian expats are found throughout Asia, the UK, US, and beyond. Understanding how Medicare works (and doesn't work) abroad is crucial—as is planning for your return. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Australian expats. Strong networks worldwide, comprehensive coverage, reliable service.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent worldwide networks. Bupa has strong Australian presence.</li>
    <li><strong>NIB Global:</strong> Australian insurer with international products. Familiar brand, includes Australia coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong European and Asian networks.</li>
    <li><strong>Medibank Global:</strong> Another Australian option with international coverage. Familiar brand for Australians.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="LHC Loading Warning"
    description="Australia's Lifetime Health Cover (LHC) loading adds 2% to private insurance premiums for each year you're over 31 without cover. Time abroad may count against you. Understand the rules before leaving."
    buttonText="Compare Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-australia">Leaving Australian Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Australia has a dual public-private healthcare system. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>Medicare</h3>
  <p>
    Medicare provides free or subsidized healthcare for Australian citizens and permanent residents. However, Medicare only works in Australia—it provides no coverage abroad except in countries with reciprocal agreements (and even then, only for emergency care).
  </p>

  <h3>Private Health Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Australian private health insurance (Medibank, Bupa, NIB, HCF) typically suspends or cancels when you move abroad. Some insurers offer "overseas absence" provisions allowing you to suspend cover for up to a few years. Check your specific policy.
  </p>

  <h3>Lifetime Health Cover (LHC) Loading</h3>
  <p>
    Australia's LHC system adds 2% to private insurance premiums for each year you're over 31 without hospital cover, up to 70% maximum. Being abroad without Australian private cover may accumulate loading—understand the exemptions before you leave.
  </p>

  <h3>LHC Exemptions</h3>
  <p>
    Certified continuous overseas absence may exempt you from LHC loading. You need to:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Be abroad continuously (brief visits to Australia are okay)</li>
    <li>Get certification of your absence upon return</li>
    <li>Take out private cover within the permitted time after returning</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="reciprocal-agreements">Reciprocal Agreements</h2>
  <p>
    Australia has reciprocal healthcare agreements with several countries:
  </p>

  <h3>Countries with Agreements</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>New Zealand:</strong> Trans-Tasman agreement provides substantial coverage</li>
    <li><strong>United Kingdom:</strong> Emergency and immediately necessary treatment</li>
    <li><strong>Ireland:</strong> Emergency and essential treatment</li>
    <li><strong>Belgium, Finland, Italy, Malta, Netherlands, Norway, Slovenia, Sweden:</strong> Limited emergency coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>What's Covered</h3>
  <p>
    Reciprocal agreements typically cover only emergency and immediately necessary treatment—not routine care, pre-existing conditions, or elective procedures. They're useful for short visits but inadequate for long-term living abroad.
  </p>

  <h3>Trans-Tasman (New Zealand)</h3>
  <p>
    The Australia-New Zealand agreement is more comprehensive than others. Australian citizens in NZ can access public healthcare similarly to NZ citizens. This is the strongest reciprocal arrangement Australia has.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Don't Rely on Reciprocal Agreements</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Even with reciprocal agreements, coverage is limited to emergency care. Comprehensive international insurance is essential for full protection—routine care, specialists, and non-emergency treatment require proper coverage.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage ideal for Australian expats. Strong networks in Asia (popular Australian expat region), Europe, and the Americas. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    24/7 English service, direct billing at major hospitals worldwide. Australia coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Australian expats who want reliable global coverage with strong networks in any region.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa has significant presence in Australia and offers excellent global coverage. Premium positioning with outstanding service quality, comprehensive benefits including mental health and maternity.
  </p>

  <p>
    Familiar brand for Australians. Australia coverage available as an add-on.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Australian expats who want premium coverage from a familiar brand.
  </p>

  <h3>NIB Global</h3>
  <p>
    NIB is one of Australia's largest health insurers and offers international products. Familiar brand, familiar processes, Australia coverage included. Good option for those who want continuity with Australian insurance.
  </p>

  <p>
    International networks are adequate, strongest in Asia-Pacific.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Australian expats who prefer a familiar Australian insurer with seamless home coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks in Europe and Asia. Good value for comprehensive coverage without the highest premiums.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Australian expats seeking good value, especially in Europe or Asia.
  </p>

  <h3>Medibank Global</h3>
  <p>
    Medibank is Australia's largest health insurer (government-owned until 2014) and offers some international products. Familiar brand, Australia coverage included. International networks more limited than dedicated international insurers.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Australian expats who want familiar Australian service and primarily need Australia coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Australian and International Options"
    description="Australian insurers offer LHC continuity options; international insurers may have stronger global networks. Consider both for your situation."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-australia">Returning to Australia</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to Australian healthcare involves re-establishing Medicare and potentially private cover:
  </p>

  <h3>Medicare Re-enrollment</h3>
  <p>
    Medicare coverage resumes automatically for Australian citizens upon return. Visit a Medicare office with proof of identity and residency to update your details. Coverage is immediate—no waiting period.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Health Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    If you suspended Australian private cover, you may be able to resume it. Contact your previous insurer. New private cover is subject to waiting periods for some benefits.
  </p>

  <h3>LHC Loading</h3>
  <p>
    If you qualify for the overseas absence exemption, you must take out hospital cover within specific timeframes after returning (typically within 12 months). Get your overseas absence certified at a Medicare office.
  </p>

  <h3>Transition Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    Keep your international insurance active briefly after returning while you sort out Australian coverage, especially if you're waiting for private cover benefits to kick in.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does Medicare cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No, except limited emergency coverage in countries with reciprocal agreements. You need international insurance for comprehensive coverage abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Will I accumulate LHC loading while abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Potentially. Certified continuous overseas absence may exempt you. Understand the rules and get proper certification when you return.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I suspend my Australian private cover?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Many insurers allow suspension for overseas absence (typically 2-5 years). Check your policy terms and maintain documentation.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about the UK reciprocal agreement?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">It covers emergency and immediately necessary treatment only. For living in the UK, you'll have NHS access as a legal resident—but private insurance provides better access.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is NIB or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">NIB offers Australian familiarity and LHC continuity options. Cigna has stronger global networks. Choose based on destination and how important Australian integration is.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What if I'm moving to New Zealand?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">The Trans-Tasman agreement provides good public healthcare access. You may still want private cover for faster access and additional benefits.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Australian expats need international insurance—Medicare doesn't work abroad, and reciprocal agreements cover only emergencies. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for reliable coverage worldwide. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage from a brand Australians know.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>NIB Global</strong> suits those who prefer an Australian insurer with potential LHC benefits. <strong>Allianz Care</strong> provides good value for European or Asian destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before leaving, understand the LHC rules and how to maintain exemption. Plan your return carefully to avoid accumulating loading. Keep documentation of your overseas absence for Medicare certification.
  </p>

</PageShell>
